							<h2>Wiederaufbau: Die erste Synagoge</h2>
							In 1945, after World War II had ended, <a href="#" onClick="$.fn.fullpage.moveTo('beginning', 1);">a Jewish congregation was newly founded by a small number of Hamburg Jews</a>. Most of them had survived the years of National Socialist rule because of their marriage to a non-Jewish spouse, which had afforded them a certain amount of protection. Hamburg’s Jewish congregation conceived itself as a uniform congregation which had no need for ritual associations and instead decided on a moderately orthodox structure in both its liturgy and its religious institutions. The new congregation’s establishment culminated in the opening of a new synagogue at Hohe Weide in 1960. However, a true revival of both liberal and conservative tradition was not able to take place for many decades.
